tate is S110, d=1 -> B0. So set S_next = 1'b0, S1_next = 1'b0, Count_next = 1'b0, Wait_next = 1'b0, B3_next = 1'b0, B0_next = 1'b1?\n                // No, B0 is not defined as an output signal. \n                // The outputs are: B3_next, S_next, S1_next, Count_next, Wait_next\n                // So actually we want to set the output signal that corresponds to the next state\n                // S110 with d=1 leads to B0\n                // The output to indicate B0 is next is... well we don't have such a signal\n                // Re-examining the specification:\n                // We want to calculate the next state for each condition. \n                // We have defined S, S1, S11, S110, B0, B1, B2, B3, Count, Wait as parameters\n                // For state S110 and d=1, we need to transition to B0\n                // Therefore in the combinational logic, we need to assign the appropriate output \n                // The state transition is: S110 with d=1 -> B0\n                // In the current implementation, we should make sure that B0 is encoded somewhere in our next state logic\n                // Since we don't actually define all those intermediate signals (B0_next, B1_next, etc.),\n                // The best way is to consider all valid state transitions in the truth table and correctly assign outputs\n                // In fact, looking at the problem statement again:\n                // \"S110  ()            --d=0--> S\n                //  S110  ()            --d=1--> B0\"\n                // So, when in S110 and d=1, next state is B0\n                // We just need to set the output signal that corresponds to B0\n                // But the outputs are B3_next, S_next, S1_next, Count_next, Wait_next\n                // There's no B0_next. \n                // What I'm doing wrong is assigning to signals that don't exist\n                // Looking at the output signals, they correspond to states:\n                // B3_next -> B3\n                /