ays go to next cycle)--> B1\"\n                // So it's definitely a state. \n                // I realize that the assignment was intended to say that even though we have limited outputs (B3_next, S_next, etc.) \n                // we still need to account for all 10 states in our logic. But only certain outputs show the next state.\n                // For S110 with d=1, it transitions to B0. \n                // Since B0 is not one of the output flags, we don't need to set a B0_next output\n                // What I should do is ensure all transitions are accounted for by setting the correct next-state flags\n                // But in that case, how can we have a transition to a state not listed in the outputs? \n                // Maybe the logic is simply wrong.\n                // Let's re-understand the instruction:\n                // \"Write code that generates the following signals:\"\n                // \"B3_next -- Assert when next-state is B3 state\"\n                // \n                // So indeed, for a given input state and inputs, we determine what the next state is. \n                // And then we assert one of these output flags to indicate which next state it is.\n                // If the next state is B0, we should set B0_next = 1\n                // But B0_next is not in the output list! \n                // Let's think differently: maybe there is a misunderstanding in the problem\n                // Let's read all possible transitions again:\n                // S -> S (d=0)\n                // S -> S1 (d=1)\n                // S1 -> S (d=0)\n                // S1 -> S11 (d=1)\n                // S11 -> S110 (d=0)\n                // S11 -> S11 (d=1)\n                // S110 -> S (d=0)\n                // S110 -> B0 (d=1)\n                // B0 -> B1 (always)\n                // B1 -> B2 (always)\n                // B2 -> B3 (always)\n                // B3 -> Count (always)\n                // Count -> Count (done_counting=0)\n            